Reopening due to the fact that I did not document this process.

For this process, I had built the SIPs using the `dspace-python` repository, with the objective of generating the SIPs in the .tgz (compressed TAR) format. I then tunneled to the server using the following:

```
ssh -L 1234:[DATASPACE_DEV]:22 pulsys@[BASTION_HOST]
```

Please note that, in order to support the copying of files over the SSH using `scp`, I needed to enable the following:

```
AllowTCPForwarding yes
```
within `/etc/ssh/sshd_config` on the server.

# Senior Theses Submissions

My approach was to use `scp -P 1234 export/Chemistry/Chemistry.tgz pulsys@localhost:~/` in order to copy these files into the home directory of `pulsys`. I then simply decompressed these into the `/tmp` directory:

```
cd /tmp
mkdir /tmp/Chemistry
cd /tmp/Chemistry
tar xvf ~/Chemistry.tgz
```

I then changed users to `dspace`:

```
sudo su - dspace
```

And invoked a modified set of commands derived from the original `tcsh` script:

```
export EPERSON="jrg5@princeton.edu"
export COLLECTION_HANDLE="88435/dsp018c97kq479"
export DEPARTMENT="Chemistry"
/dspace/bin/dspace import --add --collection $COLLECTION_HANDLE --eperson $EPERSON --mapfile "import-$DEPARTMENT.map" --source "/tmp/$DEPARTMENT" --workflow
```

Following this, I then deleted the original `tgz`:

```

```

# Doctoral Dissertations

This approach was similar to what was undertaken for the senior theses submissions, but much more manual and labor-intensive.

In order to retrieve the dissertations, one needed to SSH into the legacy DataSpace production server:

```
ssh -J [SERVICE_ACCOUNT]@[OIT_BASTION_HOST] [SERVICE_ACCOUNT]@dataspace.princeton.edu
sudo su - root
sudo su - dspace
cd dissertations/etd-ingest/sftp_upload
```

I then set a batch ID for the new set of dissertations:

```
export batch_id=20200408
```
...and create a new directory for importing these:

```
mkdir $batch_id
cd $batch_id
```

Unfortunately, at this point, the process is quite manual. I did not have the opportunity to script for this procedure:

```
sftp  dspace@[DSPACE_SFTP_HOST]
```

This will prompt one for the password. Please use the password stored in LastPass within `Shared-ITIMS-Passwords/dataspace/dataspace.princeton.edu`

One will then have the ability to search for the newly-uploaded .zip files:

```
-rw-r--r--    1 98041    pusvc    16255890 Nov 27  2019 etdadmin_upload_698620.zip
-rw-r--r--    1 98041    pusvc     1754092 Nov 27  2019 etdadmin_upload_701125.zip
-rw-r--r--    1 98041    pusvc    12005526 Nov 27  2019 etdadmin_upload_698417.zip
-rw-r--r--    1 98041    pusvc     2008759 Nov 27  2019 etdadmin_upload_698537.zip
-rw-r--r--    1 98041    pusvc    18973128 Nov 27  2019 etdadmin_upload_698097.zip
-rw-r--r--    1 98041    pusvc    20546463 Nov 27  2019 etdadmin_upload_698085.zip
-rw-r--r--    1 98041    pusvc     3124739 Nov 27  2019 etdadmin_upload_697535.zip
-rw-r--r--    1 98041    pusvc     9184066 Nov 27  2019 etdadmin_upload_698016.zip
-rw-r--r--    1 98041    pusvc     3248499 Nov 27  2019 etdadmin_upload_697355.zip
-rw-r--r--    1 98041    pusvc     9889669 Nov 27  2019 etdadmin_upload_697525.zip
-rw-r--r--    1 98041    pusvc    33621089 Nov 27  2019 etdadmin_upload_697167.zip
-rw-r--r--    1 98041    pusvc      952251 Nov 27  2019 etdadmin_upload_697183.zip
-rw-r--r--    1 98041    pusvc     9917007 Nov 27  2019 etdadmin_upload_697203.zip
-rw-r--r--    1 98041    pusvc     7065042 Nov 27  2019 etdadmin_upload_697029.zip
```

For the purposes of speed, I was simply manually selecting the files (or, downloading all files and sorting them after they had been copied over the SFTP to the DataSpace server environment).

It should be noted that all files are uploaded by date, and that all files are uploaded in a "batch" style procedure.

I then invoke a Python preprocessing script on the DataSpace legacy server:
```
cd ~/dissertations/etd-ingest
python prepare_for_import.py sftp_upload/$batch_id import/$batch_id
```

This generates a set of directories within `dissertations/etd-ingest/import/$batch_id`. Once the directories have been generated, they are copied to the dataspace-dev.princeton.edu using `scp -r` (recursion flag) while tunneling over the SSH (please see above).

My preference has been to transfer the directories on `dataspace-dev` to `/tmp`, yielding the following:

```
ls -lt /tmp/20200408
drwxr-xr-x 42 pulsys pulsys 4096 Aug  3 22:28 SUCCESS
dspace@gcp-dataspace-dev1:~$ ls -lt /tmp/20200408/SUCCESS/
total 160
drwxr-xr-x 3 pulsys pulsys 4096 Aug  3 22:28 etdadmin_upload_714935
drwxr-xr-x 2 pulsys pulsys 4096 Aug  3 22:28 etdadmin_upload_713325
....
```

One then imports these as the `dspace` user with the following:
```
sudo su - dspace
export EPERSON="jrg5@princeton.edu"
export BATCH_ID="20200408"
export MAPFILE="import-$BATCH_ID.mapfile"
export BATCH_SOURCE="/tmp/$BATCH_ID/SUCCESS"
/dspace/bin/dspace import --add --eperson $EPERSON --source $BATCH_SOURCE --mapfile $MAPFILE
```

orangelight.title: Wireframe CDL item statuses in the catalog

comments.body: Current example: https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog/679947

Scenarios:

1. There's one copy and its on CDL
2. There are 2 copies in the same location and 1of them is on CDL
3. There are 3 copies in the same location and 2 of them are on CDL
4. There are 2 copies in different locations and 1 of them is on CDL
Question for @escowles Should CDL items be requestable? Currently they can be requested for "pick-up or digitization" e.g. https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog/679947
@hackmastera No, the CDL items should not be requestable. I believe the plan is to have selectors review the CDL items and decide which to reshelve and make requestable again.

Here's one initial sketch. Thoughts / suggestions? I think doing it this way could be good because we don't have to mix the CDL link into the "in the library" info -- this way no matter how many copies are on CDL there's only one link to the checkout. @escowles 

![OL-digital-lending-UI.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5cba1f45fec3b63424e0f761/21741b81-c0b3-46ea-a0e9-10b7e493a05f)
